We'll have to agree to disagree on whether or not THIS is a customer service issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> In my eyes, giving the banker 2k and asking GM's to give it back is the same as you training/wiping your raid/group and asking for GM's to ress you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well I was kind of looking at it like this.<br>
<br>
In real life, if you go and do something illegal, you go to jail. (lets say it's an imprisonable offense) You did it, you f00ked up, and you pay the price or spend your life running and hiding. Saying I didn't mean to do that doesn't change anything as long as you did, in fact, do it.<br>
<br>
However, if you go to the bank to deposit money, but drop your money on the floor, you simply reach down and pick it up, right? The bank doesn't tell you, it touched the floor, therefore you lost it, you made a mistake, now go earn another $2000 right? They don't care as long as they know it was your money on the ground.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Take some accountability for your own actions. I dropped a rebreather I paid 2250pp for long long ago on the ground while running through Gfay. Petitioning to have it given back never even crossed my mind, why? It was my own damn fault not verant's or a bug. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
yes, but again, dropping a rebreather on the ground is different. I feel your pain, and don't mean to lessen it, but replacing the rebreather would have an effect on the economy of EQ. The reason there is a difference is that if they replaced the rebreather for you, then there would be a duplicate rebreather (droppable) on the Mith Marr Server. You could even sneak back and pick it up after you got the new one from the GM and sell your duplicate. It would have rotted you say? How do they know you don't have a second account to go pick this stuff up with and then petition you lost it on the first?<br>
<br>
With this situation, the money being given back would not affect the economy at all, nor would it affect any one elses game experience, it would simply be the equivalent of her picking her money back up off the floor at the bank in real life.<br>
<br>
That is the difference.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> LOL it's obvious you don't get the point Nerun so I'll try to clearify it a bit. I know she didn't ask for a rez my point is there's no difference. You wouldn't ask for a rez due to your own mistake but why ask for the pp back for a mistake your wife made? I used the rez thing as an example of how people make mistakes all the time, it's part of life as well as the game. You shouldn't (although it's obvious you do) expect them to fix your mistakes. Why would it be more acceptable to you to ask for the pp back but not ask for a GM rez every time you die due to a &quot;mistake&quot;?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Because your example has an effect on game balance. Player X can reach lvl 60 before Player Y who played the same amount of hours. Dying is a risk of playing the game, and we understand this. Again, we're going to have to agree to disagree on this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Hehe as to Ebelar's guess to your background I have to say I don't agree. You're probably middle class not very rich but not poor by any means. Rich people would just say &quot;bah it's only 2k&quot;. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I should apologize for being so hostile about that. I think ebelare was out of line with that statement still, but I maybe shouldn't have told him/her (?) to shut the hell up.<br>
<br>
The story is long, so I will give cliffnotes. I left home with $200 to my name when I was 18, they (my parents) kept <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> everything</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of mine, including my car that they refused to sign over to me even though I paid for it, and I had to start fresh.<br>
<br>
3 years later, I now work at Microsoft, have a nice place near Seattle, and am going to get married to my beautiful fiance who happens to be just as addicted to EQ as I am.<br>
<br>
I didn't get where I am by saying &quot;bah, 2k is chump change&quot;... I got where I am by questioning why in the hell I should have to pay $2k for (X) item or service, and having people re-examine the situation to find out I should only have to pay $1k.<br>
<br>
You can call it whining. I say that if you don't question the questionable, you're stupidly paying more than you need to.<br>
<br>
